#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "Brokering Overview"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:7
#, no-wrap
msgid "When using {project_name} as an identity broker, users are not forced to provide their credentials in order to authenticate in a specific realm.\n"
"Instead, they are presented with a list of identity providers from which they can authenticate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can also configure a default broker. In this case the user will not be given a choice, but instead be redirected directly to the parent broker.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following diagram demonstrates the steps involved when using {project_name} to broker an external identity provider:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:12
#, no-wrap
msgid "Identity Broker Flow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:14
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/identity_broker_flow.png[]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "User is not authenticated and requests a protected resource in a client application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "The client applications redirects the user to {project_name} to authenticate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:18
#, no-wrap
msgid "At this point the user is presented with the login page where there is a list of identity providers supported by a realm.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "User selects one of the identity providers by clicking on its respective button or link.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:22
#, no-wrap
msgid "{project_name} issues an authentication request to the target identity provider asking for authentication and the user\n"
"is redirected to the login page of the identity provider.\n"
"The connection properties and other configuration options for the identity provider were previously set by the administrator in the Admin Console.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "User provides his credentials or consent in order to authenticate in the identity provider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:26
#, no-wrap
msgid "Upon a successful authentication by the identity provider, the user is redirected back to {project_name} with an authentication response.\n"
"Usually this response contains a security token that will be used by {project_name} to trust the authentication performed by the identity provider\n"
"and retrieve information about the user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now {project_name} is going to check if the response from the identity provider is valid.\n"
"If valid, it will import and create a new user or just skip that if the user already exists.\n"
"If it is a new user, {project_name} may ask the identity provider for information about the user if that info doesn't already exist in the token.\n"
"This is what we call _identity federation_.\n"
"If the user already exists {project_name} may ask him to link the identity returned from the identity provider with his existing account.\n"
"We call this process _account linking_.\n"
"What exactly is done is configurable and can be specified by setup of <<_identity_broker_first_login,First Login Flow>> . At the end of this step, {project_name} authenticates the user and issues its own token in order to access the requested resource in the service provider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once the user is locally authenticated, {project_name} redirects the user to the service provider by sending the token previously issued during the local authentication.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "The service provider receives the token from {project_name} and allows access to the protected resource.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are some variations of this flow that we will talk about later.\n"
"For instance, instead of presenting a list of identity providers, the client application can request a specific one.\n"
"Or you can tell {project_name} to force the user to provide additional information before federating his identity.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "Different protocols may require different authentication flows.\n"
"      At this moment, all the identity providers supported by {project_name} use a flow just like described above.\n"
"      However, despite the protocol in use, user experience should be pretty much the same.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/server_admin/topics/identity-broker/overview.adoc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "As you may notice, at the end of the authentication process {project_name} will always issue its own token to client applications.\n"
"What this means is that client applications are completely decoupled from external identity providers.\n"
"They don't need to know which protocol (eg.: SAML, OpenID Connect, OAuth, etc) was used or how the user's identity was validated.\n"
"They only need to know about {project_name}.\n"
msgstr ""

